[2] Cholera: Malawi (school closures)
Date: Mon 2 Jan 2023
Source: Medical Xpress [edited]
https://medicalxpress.com/news/2023-01-malawi-schools-worsening-cholera-outbreak.html


Malawi shuts schools over worsening cholera outbreak
----------------------------------------------------
Schools in Malawi's 2 largest cities are to remain closed until further notice due to a worsening cholera outbreak, the government said on Monday [2 Jan 2023]. Students were due back in class after the holidays on Tuesday [3 Jan 2023] but the health ministry said the start of the school term for primary and secondary pupils in the capital Lilongwe and the southern city of Blantyre would be delayed by at least 2 weeks.

Health Minister Khumbize Chiponda said in a statement the postponement was "due to the recent and continuing increase in the number of cholera cases and deaths." Authorities regretted "any inconvenience caused by this late advice taken solely in the interest of the safety of our learners", she added. The impoverished southern African country has recorded almost 18 000 cases of the disease and 595 deaths since March [2023] in what the UN has said is the largest outbreak to hit the nation in 10 years.

Cholera is contracted from a bacterium generally transmitted through contaminated food or water. It causes diarrhea and vomiting, and can be especially dangerous for young children.

In September [2022], the WHO warned that after years of decline, the planet was witnessing a "worrying upsurge" in cholera outbreaks, with climate change adding to traditional triggers such as poverty and conflict.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[Lilongwe is located in the central plain of the country and Blantyre is in the south. - Mod.LL]

